{
  "body" : "Generate a high-design character relationship poster for【{{theme}}】. This should not be a normal illustration, but a relationship map that combines information visualization, narrative structure, poster-level design, and strong fidelity to the style of the original work.\n\nAutomatically do the following\n- identify the source work and its core setting\n- select the【{{character_count}}】most representative key characters (range 6–12, hard upper limit 15 if absolutely necessary)\n- identify and show the most important relationships, focusing on the types specified by the user:\n{{relationship_focus}}\n- use the composition pattern: 【{{composition}}】\n- extract the work's style DNA, including color palette, worldbuilding symbols, texture language, emotional tone, layout rhythm, and iconic motifs\n- convert those style elements into the overall visual design of the relationship map rather than simply copying an official poster\n- use different colors, line styles, and arrows to distinguish relationship types while keeping the layout clear and readable\n- emphasize the core characters most strongly, secondary characters next, and minor characters less prominently to create a clear visual hierarchy\n- keep every character name easy to read, optionally with role or faction tags if useful\n\nDesign aesthetic\n- Style direction: {{design_aesthetic}}\n- Label language: {{language}}\n- Each character is shown as an editorial-quality portrait (half-body or face), not a tiny icon. Portraits must stay faithful to the character's canonical look (hair, attire, identifying features).\n- Lines connecting characters: solid red = hostile, dashed pink = romance, gold = mentor, grey = neutral / acquaintance, dotted = hidden / suspected. Adapt the color logic to the chosen aesthetic, but keep a legible legend somewhere on the poster.\n\nThe final piece should\n- make the main relationships understandable at a glance\n- strongly evoke the original work's identity and setting\n- combine infographic clarity with premium poster design\n- feel unified, polished, complete, and suitable for social sharing or poster display\n- avoid cheap flowchart vibes, clutter, or information overload\n\nStrict avoid\n- Do NOT directly copy the official poster of the source work — extract its DNA and re-design.\n- Do NOT misspell character names. Names must be canonical (English / Chinese / Japanese / Korean as appropriate per the IP).\n- Do NOT draw all characters at the same visual weight — protagonists must dominate.\n- Do NOT make this a flat org-chart with rectangular boxes only. It must have poster-level visual design.\n- No watermarks, no studio logos.\n\nOutput aspect ratio: 2:3 vertical, suitable for fan posters, IP secondary creation, video essay thumbnails, social sharing.\n\n——————\nTheme: {{theme}}\nCharacter count: {{character_count}}\nComposition: {{composition}}\nRelationship focus: {{relationship_focus}}\nAesthetic: {{design_aesthetic}}\nLanguage: {{language}}\n",
